pageSummary: Challenge to complete 100 x 10k runs during 2020 because people living with cancer need our love X
pageSummaryWhat: Challenge to complete 100 x 10k runs during 2020
pageSummaryWhy: people living with cancer need our love X
story:
Hello!

I'm in the final stages of running 100 x 10k runs in 2020, and friends and family have asked if they can sponsor me as I push to complete this journey.  I do have one special person in mind as I run these challenges, but have chosen Macmillan Cancer Support as they are here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support.

Thank you to everyone who has run with me this year, through, ice, snow, blistering heat wind and rain.  Thanks for all of the kudos on Strava and likes on FB when I share my runs.  All really appreciated and motivates me to go on.  

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

As I write this I still have seven more 10K runs to go and it's the 17th December...  Better get my running shoes on!

THANK YOU!

Ian

During Steves short illness, Macmillan Cancer supported Steve and his family through a very difficult time. A charity, of which we are sure Steve would agree, is so worthy of our support 

In Memory of Steve we will be wearing our Xmas jumpers over the next week from Friday 18th December. We are sure he will be smiling down on us all (with a few choice words going on in his head 😉)......

Keep on smiling up there Steve and dont forget the battenberg!!!! 😊

pageSummary: We are braving a festive freeze on Christmas Day
pageSummaryWhat: We are braving a festive freeze on Christmas Day
story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page where we are raising as much money as we can for Macmillan Cancer Support!

On 25th December 2020, Rho, Matty and I will be braving the cold and taking a morning dip down at Bournemouth beach to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support which is a fantastic charity close to our hearts.

Our lovely mum (Alex) was diagnosed with a rare form of bowel cancer last year and as a result, required life-changing surgery. Upon diagnosis, she was sign posted to a local Macmillan group by her oncology nurse, where she received a range of help and support.

Unfortunately, a year on… it’s back. This time, mum will be undergoing chemotherapy and radiotherapy before going up to Leeds for specialist surgery in the New Year. Due to chemo and Covid mum now has to shield before she starts her treatment which sadly means we won’t be able to spend Christmas together as planned. As you can imagine, this has come as a big blow for us!

But, like last time, we know Macmillan will be there to support our mum throughout!

Macmillan- “We’re here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right there with you”.

Fundraising is hugely important to Macmillan as they rely on donations from supporters like you for 99% of their funding to provide support to cancer patients and family members. Without donations, Macmillan wouldn’t exist!

It has been a tough year for everyone, and charities have taken a huge hit. So any donation no matter how big or small, will be really appreciated!!

Sending everyone warmth and love,

MERRY CHRISTMAS!

Fii, Rho & Matty x

pageSummary: We are raising donations because Of their support to all those living with cancer
pageSummaryWhy: Of their support to all those living with cancer
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

On Saturday 5th December, my mum passed away. She had been diagnosed with lung cancer two years before and smashed through her previous prognosis.  She was a fighter. Although she had been living with cancer knowing it was terminal, her final 24 hours were unforeseen and shocked us all.  No one could have predicted the complications or hidden problems mum had developed so quickly. Covid meant we held mum's hand through latex gloves and behind full PPE as she passed away. Covid has prevented us from seeing her again in rest to say goodbye. These are awful and heartbreaking times for us. 

Macmillan provided fantastic support to mum, being there for her and contacting her to always let her know someone would always listen and understand what she was going through in what must have felt an incredibly lonely journey. 

Christmas will be a little less bright for us this year but we would love to help support others who are currently in a similar situation to where our mum was. Macmillan provide support and help to families as well, because it hurts everyone around those loved ones too. Instead of cards or, gifts, or if you are feeling festively generous, please feel free to donate to Macmillan, who change lives and help those going through the unimaginable. Thank you ❤️

story: With a family history, losses and a recent family member being diagnosed with cancer, I have decided to run a 24 Hour livestream to raise not only money but awareness for this incredible charity. The stream will consist of myself and friends playing a variety of games together, having a blast whilst we do our part in helping those who need it the most. Cancer is a horrible disease, it has taken many of my loved ones, my friends loved ones and many others. We all need to pull together and beat this once and for all. No one should face cancer alone. Let's put up a fight and give back to such a wonderful charity that work so hard to help our loved ones. All donations are welcome, big or small, it helps to give to an amazing cause. All proceeds go directly to MacMillan. Thank you for reading & your support. Josh x

story:
As many of you are aware; I was meant to complete this challenge in Sept 2020. We are now departing Feb 2021. Charities need your support more than ever before and Macmillan are busier than ever as cancer diagnosis is being postponed or missed due to the global pandemic. So for that reason  I am attempting to drag this lockdown state body up Mount Kilimanjaro......

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

pageSummary: Raising money in Loving memory of Liam McNeill
pageSummaryWhat: Raising money in Loving memory of Liam McNeill
story:
The McNeill family are raising money on behalf of their beloved husband, father and grandfather Liam, who sadly passed away on 8th December prematurely and unexpectantly due to a sudden heart attack. 

Liam is greatly missed by his wife Pauline, daughter Charlotte, son Peter, and his partner Annemarie, grandson Aidan, brother, sisters, aunts, nieces and nephews. 

Liam's life can be summarised as a family man first, he was a loyal man with strong principals on love and respect, he was  hard-working and was happiest when surrounded by his family. He also enjoyed a day at the horse races and had a great appreciation of music. He loved attending concerts, especially U2 and Meatloaf and in recent times Amy Macdonald and Future Islands.

Liam's passing has been a shock to everyone and his family are grateful for the love and support that has been shown to them during this time. They would like to help raise money for the British Heart Foundation so that others are able to get urgent treatment in time. 

 Thank you for your generosity to help The British Heart Foundation to research cures and treatments to 'Beat heartbreak forever'.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. 

Every Christmas our Dad would create a magical village/nativity scene with water features and lights amongst other things, which visitors to our house would love. Growing up it was always my favourite part of Christmas, helping him create a different scene each year, he taught me everything I know now about putting them together. So this year I have completed it in his memory and would like to raise vital funds for an amazing cause which has always been so important to us as well as lots of other people. 

Donating at JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs. 

Thank you for your donations and Merry Christmas xx

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thank you for visiting our team page.

As a team, Alice and Bryana will be running in the London Landmark Half Marathon to raise money for the British Heart Foundation on the 23rd May 2021.

The British Heart Foundation relies on this type of fundraising to allow them to continue their incremental work. This work includes developing new cures and creating new treatments for those suffering with heart and circulatory disease in the UK. The BHF have helped halve the number of people dying from these diseases, but sadly every day hundreds of people continue to lose their lives. The BHF are dedicated to supporting on-going research with the goal of decreasing this number. As little as £24 can pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist. However, every pound counts and we are extremely grateful for whatever amount you can kindly give to help support this cause.

Thank you so much for reading, and a further thank you for helping to supporting us fundraise for such an incredible charity.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
pageSummary: Doing this Christmas Charleston class because we had to cancel our planned office event
pageSummaryWhy: we had to cancel our planned office event
story:
I have been volunteering for the Guide Dog Association for over 6 years, involving Puppy walking (first 13 months of training - I took a year out),  boarding, hosting events and fundraising. 

Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation.

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss.

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society.

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

story:
We are Make Your Own Musicals, a company that specialises in creating activity packs for young people, that allow them to write and perform their own, original mini-musicals at home or in the classroom.

We are raising money for Great Ormond Street Children's Charity with our song My Kind of Christmas. Kids from across the UK have been sending in their lyrics for us to use to write a totally original song, performed by West End performers. We like to think of this as a song written by children for children.

We realise that this year has been a hard time for many, but if you feel in a position to do so, we'd love it if you could donate today. Even just a small amount goes a long way. If you can't donate today, we'd really appreciate it if you could share our video on social media.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Children's hospital, a charity very close to our hearts (GOSH Charity) . 

In October 2017, just 7 weeks after our middle son Freddie was born we was about to start a journey we never imagined. 48 hours after being admitted into hospital by an ambulance, a lumbar puncture, IV antibiotics and an oxygen machine, we was told ‘the next 24 hours were critical’ after not responding to antibiotics. I couldn’t imagine leaving the  hospital without my 7 week old baby boy, it was the worst time of my life. BUT 5 days later Freddie came home. 

Still unaware of his condition we was being told it was just bronchiolitis and would stop come the spring, April 2018 came and we lost count the times we was blue lighted into A&E back on oxygen and antibiotics. A mother’s instinct that something just wasn’t quite right so we got referred to Great Ormond Street hospital where we met the most amazing doctors and nurses who I will forever be grateful to. One consultant knew almost instantly what was going on with Freddie and after numerous tests it was confirmed Freddie had a condition called laryngeal cleft, a rare condition that will occur 1 in 20,000 births and usually happens at week 6 of pregnancy. 

On our journey at Great Ormond Street hospital I met another mum of a little boy who was 5 months old. After sharing stories of why we was there she told me her son was diagnosed with a rare blood cancer at 3 months old and was having treatment to just prolong his life, his condition was terminal. What was worse she had lost her 5 year old daughter to a heart condition the year before, just utterly heartbreaking and a lady I will never forget. What mum deserves to loose both of her children before school age!  

After an operation and a few hospital stays Freddie was ‘fixed’. We still have annual hospital checks to make sure his lungs are doing ok but he was definitely one of the lucky ones. Some children will never leave that hospital or even get to have a Christmas/birthday in their own home with their family and this is where the charity for Great Ormond Street comes in. The NHS fund the hospital with the treatments provided to the patients but making the hospital a home for hundreds of children who will never leave or get to have a Christmas/birthday at home is where they need our help with donations. They have special day staff which play with the children, supply toys whilst the sick children can’t leave, craft afternoons and much much more but without donations this wouldn’t be possible, which is why I will be running 31 miles in January to help raise money.

pageSummary: I am selling my paintings because I want to support the fight against cancer
pageSummaryWhy: I want to support the fight against cancer
story:
I have always enjoyed painting and I would love to do something good with my spare time which is why I've created this fundraiser. Cancer Research UK is a charity that is close to my heart for many reasons, so today I am opening up this page for donations, in memory of my best friend's mum.

I'll be completing 5 paintings to begin with so if you fancy commissioning me, please contact me on Instagram @ScarlettIrons (before donating!) so I can get working on something you'd like. Please also see my Instagram to get inspired if you are at all interested. I will be painting in my spare time until April 2021 and all paintings will be A4 size and on canvas.

Any donations are so appreciated, thank you for your support. 

xxx

story:
Hello all,

This year has been very difficult for charities who are doing their best make the world a better place.  My favourite charity, Cancer Research UK is no exception to this.  Given that I am now home bound and will not spending time, energy and money on festive dinners and drinks, I have decided to make a pledge to take at least 300,003 steps between 19 December and 3 January.  To make things more interesting, a few of those steps would be achieved through 100km run over the 15 days.  

I am looking at all of you to support me and Cancer Research UK with your generous donations.  I don’t need to tell you about them, they are trying to solve a problem that has impacted all of us, and every penny helps - https://www.cancerresearchuk.org/about-us

I will provide shameless daily updates on the both my progress, and the amount raised.   Please do help me spread the word, let’s see if we can make it over £10,000.

Thanks all in advance!

eventName: Lydia is shaving off her hair!
pageSummary: On New Year's Day I am going to be shaving my hair because it funds vital research!
pageSummaryWhat: On New Year's Day I am going to be shaving my hair
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This year has been a super tough one for everyone! It has unfortunately meant that fundraising has decreased and also cancer treatments and testing have been delayed. 1 in 2 people will get cancer in their lifetimes, we need to keep fighting against this. 

In March, my Mum was diagnosed with lung cancer, she was lucky and was able to have the treatment and is doing well! I have felt pretty helpless during this time, so this is me doing something to make a difference!

So, on new year's day, I am planning on shaving my hair off for cancer research. I appreciate it has been a hard year and it is Christmas, so thank you for anything you can contribute.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

pageSummary: I am raising funds because I hope to contribute to the fight against cancer.
pageSummaryWhy: I hope to contribute to the fight against cancer.
story:
Dear all

Having become a bit of a hermit during lockdown, I am in dire need of a haircut. In the interests of:

  • Helping others whenever the opportunity arises
  • And promoting sustainability/reusing what we can (‘hashtag’ love our planet!)

I have decided to go for the chop (9 inches or thereabouts) and donate my hair to charity to make wigs for cancer patients. My appointment in the afternoon on New Year's Eve.

At the same time I thought I would also set up a Just Giving page to raise money for cancer research around the event.

Cancer has effected so many people we all know over the years. My own nani (maternal grandmother) passed away from cancer just a month before I was born which always made me sad. So I hope every contribution will make a difference to fighting this disease.

Thank you so much for your generosity in advance.

Sunita

pageSummary: 50K walk across the land of ice and fire because of the vital work of this charity
pageSummaryWhat: 50K walk across the land of ice and fire
pageSummaryWhy: of the vital work of this charity
story:
Perhaps a mid-life crisis or just ready for a challenge? And of course wanting to help an amazing charity which supports living with terminal illness and their loved ones. 

Amidst COVID the need to raise funds is even more critical. Pre-COVID I had wonderful plans of face to face events and now scratching my head to consider other ways of funding. 

So my first brain wave...

My gorgeous son Kaden and his lovely friend Lewis are doing a sky dive for Kaden's 16th birthday and have agreed to do this to help me raise funds for Marie Curie. I admire you both, you are braver than me!!

I will be planning other fund-raising activities, starting with a donation instead of sending Christmas cards, and information will follow. 

In the meantime if you are able to donate I am grateful of any donation. And if anyone wants to train with me ('lazy couch to 50k') please do!

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
charity.registrationNumber: 207994 (England & Wales) and SC038731 (Scotland)
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

pageSummaryWhy: we need to help children in danger
story:
As the festive season approaches, bringing excitement to most, it unfortunately isn't the case for everyone. 


This year has been exceptionally challenging to say the least. So, now more than ever, is a good opportunity to give back to those less fortunate. After all, Christmas is for giving - not just receiving.

Thank you to everyone that helped choose which charity we should support this holiday which is UNICEF. 

UNICEF is a United Nations agency responsible for providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. The agency is among the most widespread and recognizable social welfare organizations in the world.

Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk

To help raise money for this fantastic cause, we are holding a festive charity raffle on the 17th December - so please dig deep and make a donation. Those that do well be automatically entered into our raffle and be in for a chance to win some lovely prizes! All winners will be announced on the 18th December. Good luck! 


At Genius "we believe in better together." Let's make this a Merry Christmas for all.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story:
While 2020 has not been a great year for many, we wanted to take some time, to share anything you can with those who have had it even worse than us.

Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.
